<dl id="n09179c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n09" href="#n09179c">N09 (VI.B.1)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n09all.htm#n09179c"> 179(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> slope <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n09179c"> <li>FW prototext </li><li><ms href="#n09179c">MS BL 47474-112</ms> </li><li>JJA 48:054 <a name="hd2y" href="../../FF/fdra/hda.htm#hd2y">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/h/hd2.htm#n09179c">Draft: I.8&sect;1.2</a>+</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">RIVER ENGINEERING. &hellip; <i>Physical Characteristics of Rivers &hellip; River Basins</i>.- The basin of a river is the expanse of country, bounded by a winding ridge of high ground, over which the rainfall flows down towards the river traversing the lowest part of the valley; whereas the rain falling on the outer <mark>slope</mark> of the encircling ridge flows away to another river draining an adjacent basin. <small> <a name="EBRV" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#EBRV"><cite title="source">&ldquo;RIVER ENGINEERING&rdquo;Encyclopaedia Britannica</cite></a>, 11th edit. (1911) XXIII 374</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
